'end'. If there are tool calls but finish_reason is null (some providers don't set it), I return 'tool_use'. Good.\n\nActually, I realize there's a potential issue: some OpenAI-compatible providers send `finish_reason` in the last chunk along with the last content. My code handles this — I check both delta.content and finish_reason in the same chunk.\n\nLet me also handle the case where `finish_reason` is 'tool_calls' but I haven't emitted tool-call yet — I emit tool calls after the loop. Good.\n\nOne more: the `tool-call-delta` event doesn't have an `id` field (per the contract). My code doesn't include `id`. Good.\n\nLet me write the final code now.\n\nActually, I want to reconsider whether to emit `tool-call-delta` for OpenAI. The requirement says: \"accumulate `choices[0].delta.tool_calls[].function.arguments`→tool-call-delta (emit `tool-call` when a call's args parse / on finish).\" So yes, emit tool-call-delta for each arguments chunk. Good.\n\nNow, for the `toolCallId` in `tool-call-delta`: I use `accum.id ?? ''`. On the first chunk, `accum.id` is set (from `tc.id`). On subsequent chunks, `accum.id` is already set. So it should be the real id. Good. But what if the first arguments chunk comes before the id is set? In OpenAI's format, the first tool_call chunk always has `id` and `function.name` with empty `arguments`. Subsequent chunks have only `function.arguments`. So id is always set before arguments arrive. Good.\n\nOK, final code:\n\nLet me also think about whether I need `max_tokens` for OpenAI. Not required. I'll skip it. For Anthropic, `max_tokens` is required by the API. I'll set 4096.\n\nLet me write everything now.\n\nHmm, actually for the Anthropic test, I should also verify the request headers include `x-api-key` and `anthropic-version`. But that's not strictly required by the test spec. Let me add a header capture test if easy. Actually, the fake fetch receives `init?.headers`. I could capture. But not required. Let me skip to keep tests focused