and `entry.id = 'gpt-4.1'`. The `assistant-start` uses `input.id = 'turn-1'`. The model sent on wire is `entry.id = 'gpt-4.1'`. No conflict. Good.\n\nLet me write the files.\n\nFor the `readSseLines` in both files — I'll duplicate it. It's a small function.\n\nActually, I realize there might be an issue with how `for await (const line of readSseLines(res.body))` interacts with the abort check. If the signal aborts while `reader.read()` is pending, the read throws, which propagates out of the async generator, and I catch it in the try/catch around the for-await. Good.\n\nBut what if the signal aborts between reads? I check `signal.aborted` at the top of each loop iteration. Good.\n\nOK, final output:","reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":"Let me carefully design these files.\n\nKey points:\n- ESM, strict TS, no `any`.\n- `createModelClient(entry, deps)` returns a `ModelClient`.\n- `streamTurn(input, tools, signal)` is an async generator yielding `AgentEvent`.\n- Read API key inside `streamTurn` from `(deps.env ?? process.env)[deps.provider?.apiKeyEnv ?? '']`.\n- OpenAI compat: POST `${baseUrl}/chat/completions`, stream SSE.\n- Anthropic: POST `${baseUrl ?? default}/v1/messages`, stream SSE.\n- OpenRouter no-train: `provider: { data_collection: 'deny', allow_fallbacks: true }`.\n- Abort handling.\n- Missing key → single error event.\n\nLet me think about the structure. I'll create a factory function that returns an object with `streamTurn`.\n\nLet me write the OpenAI compat client.\n\n```ts\nimport type { AgentEvent } from '../core/events';\nimport type { ModelClient, ToolSpec, TurnInput, TurnMessage } from '../core/contracts';\n\nexport interface OpenAICompatConfig {\n  baseUrl: string;\n  apiKeyEnv: string;\n  providerId: 'openai' | 'openrouter';\n}\n\nexport interface OpenAIDeps {\n  env?: NodeJS.ProcessEnv;\n  fetchImpl?: typeof fetch;\n}\n\nexport function createOpenAICompatClient(config: OpenAICompatConfig, deps: OpenAIDeps = {}): ModelClient {\n  return {\n    async *streamTurn(input, tools, signal): AsyncIterable<AgentEvent> {\n      const env = deps.env ?? process.env;\n      const apiKey = env[config.apiKeyEnv] ?? '';\n      if (!apiKey) {\n        yield { type: 'error', message: `missing API key for ${config.apiKeyEnv}` };\n        return;\n      }\n      ...\n    }\n  };\n}\n```\n\nWait, the error message should \"name the env-var NAME, never a value\". So `missing API key for ${config.apiKeyEnv}` — that names the env var name. Good. Actually the requirement says \"missing API key for <provider>\" but also \"name the env-var NAME\". Let me use the env var name to be safe: `missing API key for ${config.apiKeyEnv}`.\n\nHmm, actually re-reading: \"If the env var is missing/empty → yield a single `{ type:'error', message:'missing API key for <provider>' }` (name the env-var NAME, never a value)\". So message format is \"missing API key for <provider>\" but should name the env var name. I'll do `missing API key for ${config.apiKeyEnv}` which names the env var. That satisfies \"name the env-var NAME\".\n\nNow for the request body. OpenAI chat completions:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"model\": \"...\",\n  \"messages\": [...],\n  \"stream\": true,\n  \"tools\": [...],\n  \"provider\": { \"data_collection\": \"deny\", \"allow_fallbacks\": true }  // openrouter only\n}\n```\n\nMessages mapping: TurnMessage → OpenAI message format.\n- system/user: { role, content }\n- assistant: { role: 'assistant', content, tool_calls?: [...] }\n- tool: { role: 'tool', tool_call_id, content }\n\nTools mapping: ToolSpec → { type: 'function', function: { name, description, parameters } }\n\nNow SSE parsing. The response body is a ReadableStream<Uint8Array>. We need to read it, decode, split by lines, parse `data:` lines.\n\nLet me write a helper to read SSE from a ReadableStream.\n\n```ts\nasync function* readSseLines(body: ReadableStream<Uint8Array>, signal: AbortSignal): AsyncIterable<string> {\n  const reader = body.getReader();\n  const decoder = new TextDecoder();\n  let buffer = '';\n  try {\n    while (true) {\n      if (signal.aborted) break;\n      const { done, value } = await reader.read();\n      if (done) break;\n      buffer += decoder.decode(value, { stream: true });\n      let idx;\n      while ((idx = buffer.indexOf('\\n')) >= 0) {\n        const line = buffer.slice(0, idx).replace(/\\r$/, '');\n        buffer = buffer.slice(idx + 1);\n        yield line;\n      }\n    }\n    buffer += decoder.decode();\n    if (buffer.length > 0) {\n      // yield remaining lines\n      for (const line of buffer.split('\\n')) {\n        yield line.replace(/\\r$/, '');\n      }\n    }\n  } finally {\n    reader.releaseLock();\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but `reader.read()` can throw AbortError if signal aborts. Actually we pass signal to fetch, but the reader itself doesn't get the signal. We need to handle abort. Let me check signal.aborted before each read, and also catch AbortError.\n\nActually, when signal aborts, fetch's response body reader will throw. Let me wrap in try/catch.\n\nFor OpenAI SSE: lines look like `data: {...json...}` and `data: [DONE]`.\n\nLet me parse:\n```ts\nfor await (const line of readSseLines(body, signal)) {\n  if (signal.aborted) { yield aborted; return; }\n  if (!line.startsWith('data:')) continue;\n  const data = line.slice(5).trim();\n  if (data === '[DONE]') break;\n  const parsed = JSON.parse(data) as unknown;\n  // narrow\n}\n```\n\nNow narrowing OpenAI chunk. Shape:\n```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"...\",\n  \"choices\": [{ \"delta\": { \"content\": \"...\", \"tool_calls\": [{ \"index\": 0, \"id\": \"...\", \"function\": { \"name\": \"...\", \"arguments\": \"...\" } }] }, \"finish_reason\": null }],\n  \"usage\": { \"prompt_tokens\": 10, \"completion_tokens\": 20 }\n}\n```\n\nI'll write narrowing helpers.\n\nFor tool_calls accumulation: each delta has `index`, and may have `id`+`function.name` (first chunk) or `function.arguments` (subsequent). I'll accumulate per index.\n\n```ts\ninterface ToolCallAccum {\n  index: number;\n  id?: string;\n  name?: string;\n  argsBuffer: string;\n}\n```\n\nWhen finish_reason is 'tool_calls' or stream ends, emit tool-call events with parsed args.\n\nActually, the requirement: \"emit `tool-call` when a call's args parse / on finish\". So I can emit tool-call when args JSON.parse succeeds, or on finish. Let me emit on finish (when we see finish_reason or [DONE]) to be safe — accumulate all args then parse.\n\nActually, let me emit tool-call for each accumulated tool call when finish_reason === 'tool_calls' or when [DONE] is reached and there are pending tool calls.\n\nLet me think about stop reason mapping:\n- finish_reason 'stop' → 'end'\n- finish_reason 'length' → 'max_tokens'\n- finish_reason 'tool_calls' → 'tool_use'\n- finish_reason 'content_filter' → 'error'\n- abort → 'abort'\n\nNow text-delta: yield when delta.content is present.\nreasoning-delta: OpenAI doesn't really send reasoning in compat mode, but o1 models might. Skip for OpenAI compat (or handle if present). I'll check for `delta.reasoning_content` (some providers) and emit reasoning-delta. Actually let me keep it simple but handle `reasoning` field if present.\n\nLet me write the OpenAI compat client fully.\n\nFor the registry:\n\n```ts\nexport function createModelClient(entry: ModelEntry, deps: ProviderDeps = {}): ModelClient {\n  const providerId = entry.provider as ProviderId;\n  const providerConfig = deps.provider ?? {};\n  const apiKeyEnv = providerConfig.apiKeyEnv ?? '';\n  const baseUrl = providerConfig.baseUrl ?? '';\n  switch (providerId) {\n    case 'openai':\n      return createOpenAICompatClient({ baseUrl: baseUrl || 'https://api.openai.com/v1', apiKeyEnv, providerId: 'openai' }, { env: deps.env, fetchImpl: deps.fetchImpl });\n    case 'openrouter':\n      return createOpenAICompatClient({ baseUrl: baseUrl || 'https://openrouter.ai/api/v1', apiKeyEnv, providerId: 'openrouter' }, { env: deps.env, fetchImpl: deps.fetchImpl });\n  